{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/palliative-care-oral/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"047eef6e-58db-5c3e-bbc9-a5b23171e78a","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 0d8b5cd0-d789-4c1e-805b-6e6b3dc91caa --><h2>Prevalence of oral problems in palliative care</h2><!-- end field 0d8b5cd0-d789-4c1e-805b-6e6b3dc91caa -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item df7cdd14-ee70-4483-a1e6-52c36db5ca1c --><!-- begin field 477b5e08-c275-4792-836d-c59694373630 --><p><strong>Oral problems reflect the person's general health and therefore become increasingly common with advancing illness.</strong></p><ul><li>Oral problems are very common in people in a palliative situation. A review article reported that active dental caries were found in 20-35% of cases and that active gingivitis was present in 36% of people who were terminally ill [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Saini et al, 2009</a>].</li><li>Oral problems are common, and often predictable, after chemotherapy and head and neck radiotherapy.</li><li>Dry mouth was reported by 88% of patients with advanced cancer in a one-to-one survey (n = 99). Medication use was one of the most common causes. The same study stated that 16% of people reported mouth pain [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Oneschuk et al, 2000</a>].</li><li>Candidiasis (defined by the person having both clinical and microbiological evidence of oral candidiasis) was diagnosed in 30% of people with cancer (n = 120) in a prospective observational study [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Davies et al, 2006</a>].</li><li>Excessive salivation is uncommon in advanced cancer, apart from cancers of the head and neck [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Davies,&nbsp;2015</a>].</li><li>Taste sensation is diminished in 25â€“50% of people with cancer [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Davies,&nbsp;2015</a>].</li><li>Oral mucositis develops in:<ul><li>Approximately 40% of people receiving chemotherapy [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Davies and Finlay, 2005</a>].</li><li>Nearly all patients who receive radiotherapy to the head or neck develop oral mucositis. A systematic review of 33 studies (n = 6181) of people with head and neck cancer receiving radiotherapy with or without chemotherapy found that the mean incidence of mucositis was 80% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Trotti et al, 2003</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 477b5e08-c275-4792-836d-c59694373630 --><!-- end item df7cdd14-ee70-4483-a1e6-52c36db5ca1c -->","topic":{"id":"ba62b1ab-ffea-5bce-8fd6-6127df66395a","topicId":"dc5a4c25-cbc0-4da8-9263-892c0ddb29be","topicName":"Palliative care - oral","slug":"palliative-care-oral","lastRevised":"Last revised in October 2018","chapters":[{"id":"92b78ff5-a7a3-533b-9fad-3812221a3e70","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e63cc0ed-d679-5b57-bd5d-a0fffc2bb1c5","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0d446cc8-8026-59f2-8be3-a3df05f54690","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"94667ccb-b451-5743-aeb8-44fbce6caf13","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"d267c387-0c44-5636-b186-efd35314ddb7","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"b1959eca-8652-570a-bf43-e03f35359c72","fullItemName":"Goals and outco